metadata.name: Outside your Window #81
metadata.description:
Never take for granted that we sit in the safety of our homes, behind our windows, sheltered from the elements outside. 

The characteristics of the rain outside the window, and the window itself, will be determined by the mint hash. However, the background color of this piece will constantly change based on the hour of day it is loaded, hence note that the thumbnail will only technically be accurate 1/24 hours out of the day as it represents a static snapshot taken at the time of token rendering.

100% of the primary proceeds will be donated towards flood relief efforts for the devastating December 2021 floods in Malaysia.

Made in p5js
Created December 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: GuilCity #82
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet’s densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew’s (@frostbitten’s) magic touch.

Matthew—with his background in coding and animation—enables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you’ve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

—

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

—

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
• https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

—


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others’ skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci à tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: NEW TERRITORIES #17
metadata.description:
On desktop, open project in live view
Rotate and zoom with the mouse to explore the model
Click “S” to download STL 3D model file
Click “P” to download PNG file (3600x3600)


New Territories

New Territories is the sequel to Cityblocks. In this series, urban ensembles are generated with a simple click. With each iteration appears a new densely built city block. Graced with impeccable geometrical lines, devoid of any human presence, these buildings remind us of brutalist utopias like Le Corbusier’s Cité radieuse or Niemeyer’s Brasilia. But despite their clearly modernist feel, there is something hauntingly primitive about them. They could be either New Mexican adobe pueblos, Minoan palaces, or Turkish troglodyte dwellings. Both carved and sculpted, these Ghormenghasts of concrete float in a realm out of time, like in some architect’s dream.

The purpose of this creative work is to generate 3D architectural projects that could be implemented in the real world. The accelerating lives that we live, complicated by growing and unpredictable environmental crises, call for an enhanced capacity to come up quickly with new architectural solutions adapted to different contexts. From computer assisted design to 3D printing, from augmented reality to real-life housing, from sculpture to architecture, this work aims at bridging the gap between the virtual and the tangible.

Working as a visual artist, David Umemoto draws inspiration from his training as an architect. He has been using low-tech methods for a long time, refining his talent for elegant simple shapes and combinatory constructions. Now, poured concrete and home-made moulds are giving way to zero-gravity rotating models. The skills he developed while working with real objects find a new playground in the virtual realm.

metadata.name: Vorticity #27
metadata.description:
Vorticity is a gpu-accelerated flow field. The particles in the flow field orbit around a set of points that move around over time.

Controls: Click and drag to push particles away. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation a single step. Press "r" to restart the simulation (if you change the resolution of the screen after the page loads, you will need to restart to update the resolution).

metadata.name: Chaotic Growth #9
metadata.description:
Chaotic growth is based on a modified version of the differential line algorithm by Anders Hoff [1]. This algorithm uses an attraction-repulsion-model to imitate growth on a connected set of nodes. 

In this piece I explored an adaption of this algorithm attempting to visualize systems growing past their point of sustainability, creating new dynamics and eventually spiraling out of control. Some iterations may grow smoothly for some time but will quickly turn into a chaotic system of unsustainable growth. The smooth and organic shape of growth in the beginning is contrasted by the spikey, incoherent offshoots. 


Created in Vanilla JS.

Controls:
S - Save image
Space - Pause/Unpause


Best viewed in Chrome. Different browsers may produce slightly different outputs.

[1] https://inconvergent.net/generative/differential-line/

metadata.name: TO THE AIR #17
ZigZag Garden #100
metadata.description:
A generative garden drawn with zig-zag lines.
8 different color palettes and various different vegetation-densities.

In Live-Mode...
...press 'r' to toggle square/full-screen ratio.
...press 'p' to overlay the basic color-palette
...press ‘1’ - ‘6’ for high-res downloads (the higher the number the higher the resolution)

Open two different tokens of 'ZigZag Garden' with the same browser to mix their colors!

Created with p5.js using post5 and map2.

-@TeNinEightNFTs
